body:
My guess is that you have a conflict between versions of tensorflow and deeplabcut after updating one or there other.

Please post more about your installation and the error. You can copy and paste from the command line rather than a screen grab.

Also, activate your env, and run `conda list`, and paste the list here between two sets of three ticks, like:

\`\`\`
PASTE OUTPUT HERE
\`\`\`

> You don’t have 2.3rc3.
> 
> `pip install deeplabcut[gui]==2.2rc3`

This has solved the problem for me. Can't describe how excited I am right now. Thanks!

You are correct, this was the problem. This comment actually solved it for me:https://github.com/DeepLabCut/DeepLabCut/issues/1368#issuecomment-872490854

if you use the pip upgrade feature rather than the install feature it doesn't give you the newest update. I was having trouble getting this to work and that comment (single quotes rather than double quotes) was why. Changing the quotes out made it work!

Hi! I am trying to install DLC on a GPU Supercomputer node, which already has Tensorflow (2.3.0) installed. When I try `pip install deeplabcut`, and then try to import DLC I get the same error message others have gotten. However, when I try `pip install 'deeplabcut[gui]==2.2rc3'` it tries to update my Tensorflow, which then messes up my PATH and points TF to incorrect Cuda DLLs... Is there some way to get this working without altering my TF installation?
Oh my gosh thank you so much! This has been a real pain!
No problem; in general for HPCs I’d recommend Docker - much easier to manage in the long run!
